=== Etymology 1 ===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|knight|lang=enm}}, {{term|kniht|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|cniht|lang=ang}}, {{term|cneht|lang=ang}}, {{term|cneoht||boy, youth, servant, attendant, retainer, disciple, warrior, boyhood, junior member of a guild|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|knehtaz|lang=gem-pro}} (compare Dutch {{term|knecht|attendant, servant|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Knecht|lad”; “slave|lang=de}}), originally ‘billet (wood), block of wood’ (compare Dutch {{term|laarzeknecht|boot-jack|lang=nl}}, dialectal German {{term|Knüchtel|bat, club|lang=de}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|gnegʰ-|lang=ine-pro}}, from {{recons|gen-|lang=ine-pro}} ‘to ball up, pinch, compress’.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[warrior]], especially of the [[Middle Ages]].
#: ''King Arthur and the '''Knights''' of the Round Table''
# Nowadays, a person on whom a [[knighthood]] has been conferred by a [[monarch]].
# {{chess}} A [[chess piece]], often in the shape of a [[horse]]'s head, that is moved two squares in one direction and one at right angles to that direction in a single move, leaping over any intervening pieces.

